<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Joint submission to Environmental Audit Committee from the Kyoto Club, Consorzio Italiano Compostatori, Assobioplastiche and Novamont SpA</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Novamont, the Kyoto Club, The Italian Association of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and the Italian Composting Association </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are a group of Italian organisations looking to provide the Committee with information on the effect of a ban on single use-plastic bags in Italy (with exemptions for dual-use compostable bags).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The measure has had a number of benefits for the re-industrialisation of the European and Italian chemical sector, as well as benefits to organic recycling and agricultural industries and the Italian Environment.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The policy measure has helped the support emergence of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> industry (plastics made from starch and vegetable oils) at a time when its traditional chemical industry is faltering. This sector is far less reliant on petrochemicals.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The introduction of compostable bags has increased the level and quality of organic recycling – which has been beneficial to both the farming and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biowaste</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> industries. It has also reduced the costs of disposal (landfill and incineration) for local Government.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There has been a decline in the volume of plastic litter in the marine environment.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This kind of “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecoinnovation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inline</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with EU strategies on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Bioeconomy</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Resource Efficiency</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Smart Specialisation.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Finally, it is important not to confuse compostable bags, with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oxo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-degradable bags which lack all of these advantages.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Information and interests of those responsible for this submission:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submission has been jointly prepared </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by a group </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of four Italian organisations with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">shared vision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to create a circular </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioeconomy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We believe sustainably produced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioplastic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> products can help encourage a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioeconomy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (and by extension a reduction in environmental impact) through improved organic recycling. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our submission intends to explain to the committee the impact of a ban on single-use plastic bags in Italy and highlight how the UK can learn from Italy’s experiences. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The organisations are as follows:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Novamont - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> manufacturer of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> made with starch, vegetable oils (e.g. thistle, sunflower) and other renewable agricultural materials with a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n annual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">turnover of €125M. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Novamont produced compostable plastics for the 2012 Olympic Games, and already work with the Co-op supermarket chain and many local councils.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Kyoto Club</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a not for profit organisation, officially founded in February of 1999, made up of companies, organisations, associations and local governments committed to achieving the goals of reducing emissions of greenhouse gases employed under the Kyoto Protocol.</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To achieve these objectives, the Kyoto Club promotes awareness-raising, information and training in use of renewable materials. As a partner of public decision-makers, the Kyoto Club is also committed to stimulating targeted and incisive proposals and policy interventions in the energy-environment.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Assobioplastiche</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Italian Association of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Biodegradable and Compostable Materials - was formed in 2011 and represents companies operating in Italy and overseas, who are active in the production of biodegradable polymers and finished products and end of life management of products made with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Consorzio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Italiano</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Compostatori</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (CIC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Italian Composting Association unites public and private companies, local authorities and others involved in the production of compost, as well as organizations which do not make compost but have an interest in the composting process (producers of machinery and equipment, producers of fertilisers, research bodies etc.).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A general overview of the impacts of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Italian </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Plastic Bag </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Law</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 2011, Italy became the first country in the EU to introduce a law prohibiting the distribution of single use plastic bags. Since being passed in March 2012, the law has seen a r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">educ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consumption of plastic bags, and the associated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">environm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">en</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tal impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s. And, led by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">industrial and societal symbiosis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">development of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a circula</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r economy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A circular economy is one that which requires that energy come from renewable resources and that biological materials, such as food waste, are returned to the organic and economic cycles.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The law was aimed at reducing the environmental contamination caused by traditional plastic bags. With this in mind, and to help support the Italian </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> industry, an exemption was allowed for compostable bags.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Since its introduction, the new law has helped reduce the consumption of carrier bags by 33% (from 145kton 2010 to 97kton in 2012). In 2011, Italian producers of films and biodegradable compostable bags i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ncreased their workforce </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and through investment in research and new machinery a further 500 jobs were created (according to Plastic Consult).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This level of investment would not have been made possible without the policy certainty created by the new law.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">intended </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consequence of the law was the exploitation of legislative loopholes – namely the lack of a clear requirement to comply with the European Norm for compostable plastics (EN13432:200</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As such there has been a proliferation of plastic bags claiming to be biodegradable; these products gained their biodegradable status because of weak certification processes and a system of self-declarations. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This loophole was closed in 2013 with the introduction of a new law and fiscal penalties, but this serves to prove the need for any exemptions to be specific with penalties for breaches.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Environmental impact of the Italian Plastic Bag Law:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Italy’s tourism industry is dependent on a clean marine environment. Single use plastic bags make up the majority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of pollution in the marine environment. As such, action had to be taken by the Italian Government. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Degradable bags offer a potential solution to the problem of build up of plastic waste in the sea. The paragraphs below explain in more detail.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With more than 8,000 km of coastline, Italy is badly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">affected</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by plastic litter in the marine environment – particularly as any deterioration in the environment impacts tourism - a fundamental economic resource for the country. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In March 2011, the Environmental Protection Agencies of Tuscany and Emilia Romagna carried out an environmental survey which revealed that 73% of human-origin waste found on the seabed is made up of plastic bags of various sizes. Further monitoring has revealed that 95% of the large-scale refuse floating in the Tyrrhenian Sea is made up of plastic, 41% of this being made up of plastic bags and fragments.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Conventional plastics are strongly resistant to biodegradation, and tend to build up in the marine environment if not properly disposed of. Moreover many studies show that, in the long term, plastic bags are transformed in small fragments of dimension and concentration similar to plankton with the risk of entering in the food chain. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The European Standard, EN13432:200</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, used to determine biodegradation of packaging items was established to verify biodegradation for composting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">purposes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 2012, an Italian study investigated biodegradation in different marine habitats and the tests indicated that the EN13432:200</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> compostable films biodegraded to a substantial extent (88% in 236 days) in conditions replicating the sea bed and had completely disappeared on the shoreline tests. These results mirrored those of Plymouth University who found that compostable bags fully degraded (disappeared completely) in 24 weeks in Queens Anne Battery Marina unlike the conventional or pro-oxidant (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oxo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-degradable) polythene which showed almost no change (max 2%) in 40 weeks.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Studies as to how the measure has affected waste going into the marine environment are ongoing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sectoral</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> impact of the Italian Plastic Bag Law – the Chemicals industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Italian chemicals industry – due </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in part </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to high feedstock costs has been in long term decline. The emergence of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> industry – underpinned by a legal system which supports the development of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has played a role in reversing this decline, and reduced the fossil fuel dependence of the industry. See below for detail.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">From the 1930s until the 1990s, Italy was one of the world’s leading research and manufacturing hubs for plastics. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition, up </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">until 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Italy was (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">per capita</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Europe’s largest consumer of flexible plastic packaging and in particular carrier bags.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, the combination of overexpansion, increased competition from cheaper imports and a lack of enforced regulation over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> meant that Italy’s global position in the traditional chemical market declined significantly. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">During the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">conomic crisis of 2009, the fragility of the industry was further exposed and multinational chemical companies across the country were forced to close their older facilities. The industrial crisis was compounded further by the relative cost of naphtha (€761 / tonne in Italy v €93 / tonne in the Middle East) meaning the traditional plastics industry was increasingly concentrated outside of Italy and Europe and into Asia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">...</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Consequently, Italy went from being a leader in manufacturing and exports to being a net importer (7% of internal production against 19% imports). A situation not dissimilar to that of the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rising oil costs and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> desire to commercially apply green chemistry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">saw the emergence of companies like Novamont and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Coldiretti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – who sought to use locally sourced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioproducts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (such as thistles, corn and sunflowers) to produce new types of plastic.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The developme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt of a new industry using innovative</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> biotechnology to produce biodegradable and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biobased</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> plastics in Italy is continuing to thrive. A prime example of this is the Joint Venture between ENI-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Versalis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Novamont in Porto Torres in Sardinia. The Porto Torres petrochemical facility is one of Italy’s most important industrial chemical facilities but due to the decline in the overall industry it has in recent years been in crisis. The new joint venture – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Matrica</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> - will see investments of €500M to convert part of the facility into the world’s first third generation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biorefinery</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to produce new materials from locally sourced agricultural resources such as the non-food crop, cardoon grown on marginal and previously contaminated land. The investment will see seven new industrial facilities to produce not just </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biolubricants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biofillers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and additives. It is estimated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Matrica</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> alone with create a work force of 690 jobs.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Beyond </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Matrica</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, investments are seeing the redevelopment of other disused industrial facilities including a fermentation plant in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Adria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> / Veneto to produce renewable-sourced chemical intermediates used in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. There is also a “magnet” effect, non-Italian companies such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cereplast</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (USA), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Roquette</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (Fr) and DSM (NL) have decided to invest in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bioplastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and biochemical intermediates.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are currently watching the evolution of policy in the UK, if the Government signals that it is supportive of compostable plastics and regulates accordingly we may consider investment in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – as we would prefer to manufacture the bags locally if demand is great enough – which would create new jobs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sectoral</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> impact of the Italian Plastic Bag Law – the agricultural and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">biowaste</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The plastic bag law has supported Italy’s drive to reduce food and garden waste going to landfill. In addition, it has lead to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> improved quality of material being composted or digested. This has substantial benefits for the agricultural sector.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The following paragraphs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">outline these benefits in more detail.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 1992, landfill costs in northern Italy, and in particular</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Lombardy, were as low as £8 / tonne. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here were no legislative requirements for any form of diversion.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, the sudden closure of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Milan’s largest landfill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">led to a dramatic spike in the costs of landfill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – with costs rising to £80 / tonne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> within the year </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">waste </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">even </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> transported to Switzerland for incineration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. By 2005, the price for landfill has risen to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nearly £120 / </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tonne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At the same time, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">despite some government assistance, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">agriculture in Italy has been in decline. I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n recent years the high costs, particularly associated with labour, fuel and fertilisers have led to a drop in the number of farms. Between 1982 and 2010, over 3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> million</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hectares </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of arable land have been</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lost.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the cost of treating food waste </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through composting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is less than half </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the cost of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">landfill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the composting industry has seen significant investment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Most </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recent figure</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s show that over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">four and a half </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">million tonnes of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biowaste</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (food and garden waste)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">organically recycled through anaerobic digestion and / or composting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a year </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in Italy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This industry now h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as an annual turnover of €400M. For comparison, the total municipal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biowaste</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sent for organic recycling in England in 2012 was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> roughly five </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">million </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tonnes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the industry has an estimated annual turnover of £200M and employs over 1,000 full time staff.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Since 1992 the most common tools for collecting food waste in Italy are a small cont</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ainer (7 – 10l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) and compostable liners for use in the kitchen and a larger outdoor container (25l) which is emptied twice a week. Following a visit by WRAP to Novamont and northern Italy in 2006, this system of collecting food waste has become increasingly common in the UK with over ten million households receiving a food waste collection where compostable liners are accepted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Simply collecting materials is half the battle – t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he importance of quality </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">feedstock</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for efficient organic recycling cannot be over stated. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The presence of components that are not completely degradable in a composting feedstock poses a significant risk to the environment. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In order to meet the defined quality standards for composted materials the organic recycling industry has to extract the non-biodegradable fraction. Despite the best efforts of local authority collection services, the quantity of non-biodegradable contaminants in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">feedstock</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> presented for organic recycling in Italy and the UK is a serious concern. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over the past decade, substantial data has been collected which supports the need to implement separate collection of bio-waste (including kitchen, agriculture and green waste) to recover valuable resources for soil enhancement while decreasing GHG emissions. Separate collection of municipal as well as commercial bio-waste as the steering principle in bio-waste recycling via composting or anaerobic digestion would constitute the highest level of environmental benefit as well as economic viability. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Italy, the CIC have calculated that at least 53,000 T of non-compostable plastics have to be removed and sent for disposal each year at a cost of €10-12M. In England, according to the median data of the WRAP ASORI survey for 2012, the quantity of non-compostable plastic is in the region of 64,000T costing the industry at least £15M / year (based on data from the REA).  To put this in context, the latest RECOUP survey shows that less than 7,000T of household plastic film was collected for recycling in 2012. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A study released by CIC has found that impurities in biodegradable waste streams have decreased by 8% and as a result compost is less contaminated by plastic waste. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This has happened because the public recognise compostable carrier bags as an equivalent to a caddy liner bag for collection organic waste. Compostable carrier bags now represent a strategic tool to implement high performing organic waste collection schemes and are strongly supported by the CIC and by the Italian Association of the Local Authorities (ANCI)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Trials carried out in conjunction with the Co-operative Supermarket chain in the UK have shown that compostable bags have reduced the volume of waste going to landfill and quality of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">food waste</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> collected by councils.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Compostable flexible films have also been shown to be compatible with the current collection and treatment stream of conventional plastic packaging up to 10%. These are the conclusions of the study carried on by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Conai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (Italian Consortium for Packaging Recycling).  Although the reality is the compostable bags are used mainly for organic recycling of food waste and not sent for recycling with traditional plastics.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is estimated that the policy has so far saved Italy €5.1m in landfill costs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Public perception of the law</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Recent surveys show that most Italians (94%) believe that the law is an important milestone for the environment, while 88% recognise that biodegradable compostable plastics are an important innovation capable of triggering multiple positive effects (i.e. green attitudes, new green jobs, etc.) (ISPO data)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The EU Context</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Directive 94/62/EC on Packaging and Packaging Waste defines organic recycling as “the aerobic (composting) or anaerobic (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">biomethanization</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) treatment, under controlled conditions and using micro-organisms, of the biodegradable parts of packaging waste, which produces stabilized organic residues or methane”.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over the past decade, substantial data were collected supporting the need to implement separate collection of bio-waste (including kitchen, agriculture and green waste) to recover valuable resources for soil enhancement while decreasing GHG emissions. Separate collection of municipal as well as commercial bio-waste as the steering principle in bio-waste recycling via composting or anaerobic digestion would constitute the highest level of environmental benefit as well as economic viability.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">8.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Since the introduction of the Italian law, the EU has moved to introduce measures to restrict the consumption of single use plastic bags across the EU. On November 27, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">European Parliament Environment Committee voted on a number of amendments to the European Strategy on Plastic Waste in the Environment including:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8.3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hat the most dangerous plastics, those that by scientific evidence are shown to be the most disruptive to human health and the environment (such as micro- and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oxo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‐biodegradable plastics) and those which contain heavy metals and other substances that can also make recycling processes more difficult, should be phased out of the market or banned outright, as soon as possible before 2020</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8.3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">single-use, non-recyclable, non-biodegradable and non-compostable plastic bags should be radically reduced and where possible phased out</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">9.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The effectiveness of measures to reduce the use of single-use carrier bags can be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increased with exemptions for compostable bags.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">9.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Unlike single-use bags these compostable bags have significantly lower environmental impact – and can completely biodegrade quickly in most natural environments. They have no further impact on wildlife or the food chain.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">9.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The compostable bio-plastics industry is a research driven sector, and an alternative to the traditional European petrochemical industry which is struggling to compete with high fuel costs outside Europe.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">9.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Compostable bags can play a significant role in the reducing the volume of food waste going to landfill – and improve the quality of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">compostable materials passed onto the agricultural sector. By providing them through supermarkets it can reduce the costs to councils of providing compostable bin liners.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">9.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The measure has been shown to complement the recycling of single-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use plastics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">9.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The policy measure is popula</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r with the Italia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n public.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> European Commission: Innovating for Sustainable Growth – COM2012 (60) Final.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> European Commission: A resource-efficient Europe – Flagship initiative under the Europe 2020 strategy.</span></p></body></html>